<br>
There have been lots of stuff that has frustrated me at certain times, but I must say I am basically happy with my class now and have enjoyed the game more than it has bothered me.&quot;<br>
<br>
I'll take a stab at this one.  <br>
<br>
Yes, there is a point where you say &quot;Enough is enough&quot; and leave the game.  However, as any player knows, EQ takes a LOT of time.  It is a serious investment.  I mean, say you take up tennis and there's just one tennis court in the area.  You buy the gear, train and eventually reach a decent level of proficiency.  You enjoy doing it and the owner of the tennis court makes a decent living too.  <br>
<br>
But next thing you know service declines a little.  The courts aren't as nicely kept.  Are you gonna quit playing tennis altogether?  Are you gonna drive way across town to the other court?  A couple weeks later they start charging for parking.  Then a few weeks after that the court fees go up 20%.  <br>
<br>
So what was essentially a mutually beneficial situation now turns into one where the two parties are barely able to tolerate each other.  To me, this is as the old saying goes: Penny wise, pound foolish.<br>
<br>
I have several friends that got into Phantasy Star Online for the Dreamcast and I knew that EQ was the superior game in a lot of ways.  I could have gotten them to try it out and maybe become regular players.  Why didn't I do it?  Because I'm not gonna brag up a game that requires 30+ megs of patches the very first time you load it.  Oh well, Sony loses money.<br>
<br>
But for existing subscribers, there is a lot we like about the game but why, ultimately, do we play?  To have FUN, that's why.  And you know what?  When some Sony/VI jagass keeps screwing with my fun at every opportunity I have less of it than if they would just back off and respect their customers a bit more.<br>
<br>
Am I even going to play Galaxies?  I don't think so.  I have enough invested in my EQ character that I want to see him get to level 60 and see some epic content.  After that, I think I'm done with MMORPGs.  While there are some very compelling reasons to play them, the time investment coupled with the constant hassles is just not as fun for me as playing other online games. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uketherami.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kether Am I</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 501<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/8/02 2:03:39 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: My EQ Legends Journal....Some info</span><hr size=1> The only part that annoys me regarding the 'Legends' idea is that it is CLEAR that parts of SoL are NOT done.  They were hyped in the months leading up to it but are NOT in the game yet.  The different 'teams' talk is BS.  I have worked in various companies and 'teams' are made and changed on the fly.  I am SURE they did NOT hire all entirely NEW people to make that 'legends' team.  At BEST they moved some experienced people from the live team there and then hired new people to fill out both teams.<br>
<br>
The 'new server' reason is BS.  It won't be 'new' just new to you.  The only playstyle reasons for going over are:<br>
<br>
1. You like the name (dumb, but a reason)<br>
2. To leave your current server (can go to any Server for this)<br>
3. To be a part of the formation of server guild dynamics (like getting in the gorund floor of the power guild)<br>
4. To be amongst other people who are there.  That is elminating the people who aren't willing to pay $40 per month.<br>
5. For the gizmos<br>
6. For the better CS and GM interaction.<br>
<br>
<br>
Of the above, 1-3 are very spurious.  Number 4 is elitist (but believe me I do see the attraction to that sometimes).  Number 5 is cute, but isn't cute enough for an extra $360/yr.<br>
So, it comes down to number 6.  There is a problem with number 6, it is HIGHLY SUBJECTIVE.<br>
<br>
IF VI can NOT achieve objective standards (new interface, PC merchants) as 'marketed' I can NOT see how people have faith in them to meet their OWN subjective standard for such activity.  Their standard most likely being FAR higher than what VI intends.<br>
<br>
IF the new CS/GM services brought with it NEW, UNIQUE, FUN encounters that presented a dynamic world full of adventure it WOULD be worth $40 for me.  BUT, the truth is I *highly* doubt that would be the case.  Unless they hire a lot of creative and innovative people (= good salaries) I don't see it happening.  Before very long the mechanics of the game will make all the special events seem very formulaic.<br>
<br>
Maybe they can pull it off.  But as long as they can't afford to devote the time necessary to fix core issues with the software I don't see them paying the salaries necessary to reach my idea of an interactive game world.  Old server + orc invasion of FP != my ideal.<br>
<br>
